==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|la|decrepitare}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|de-}} + {{m|la|crepitare}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/dɪˈkɹɛpɪteɪt/|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|decrepitat}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[roast]] (a [[salt]] or [[mineral]]) until it stops [[crackling]] in the fire.
#* '''1646''', Sir Thomas Browne, ''Pseudodoxia Epidemica'', Folio 2007, p. 333:
#*: so will it come to pass in a pot of salt, although '''decrepitated'''; and so also in a pot of Snow.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of [[salts]] and [[minerals]], to [[crackle]] when heated, indicating a sudden breakdown of their particles.
#* {{quote-magazine|magazine=Magazine of Popular Science, and Journal of the Useful Arts|year=1837|passage=It is, however, remarkable, that the greater number of bodies which '''decrepitate''', are really anhydrous and fixed, such as sulphate of potash, sulphate of barytes, chloride of sodium, &c.|page=77}}

